# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: data-execution-prevention
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] In programming and information security, a **buffer overflow** or **buffer overrun** is an anomaly whereby a program writes data to a buffer beyond the buffer's allocated memory, overwriting adjacent memory locations.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Buffers are areas of memory set aside to hold data, often while moving it from one section of a program to another, or between programs.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Buffer overflows can often be triggered by malformed inputs; if one assumes all inputs will be smaller than a certain size and the buffer is created to be that size, then an anomalous transaction that produces more data could cause it to write past the end of the buffer.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] If this overwrites adjacent data or executable code, this may result in erratic program behavior, including memory access errors, incorrect results, and crashes.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Exploiting the behavior of a buffer overflow is a well-known security exploit.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Files specifically created to exploit buffer overflow vulnerabilities are often called 'crafted' files.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] On many systems, the memory layout of a program, or the system as a whole, is well defined.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Buffers are widespread in operating system (OS) code, so it is possible to make attacks that perform privilege escalation and gain unlimited access to the computer's resources.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The famed Morris worm in 1988 used this as one of its attack techniques.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Bounds checking can prevent buffer overflows, but requires additional code and processing time.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Modern operating systems use a variety of techniques to combat malicious buffer overflows, notably by randomizing the layout of memory, or deliberately leaving space between buffers and looking for actions that write into those areas ("canaries").
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] A buffer overflow occurs when data written to a buffer also corrupts data values in memory addresses adjacent to the destination buffer due to insufficient bounds checking.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This can occur when copying data from one buffer to another without first checking that the data fits within the destination buffer.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] In the following example expressed in C, a program has two variables which are adjacent in memory: an 8-byte-long string buffer, `a`, and a two-byte big-endian integer, `b`.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Initially, `a` contains nothing but zero bytes, and `b` contains the number 1979.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Now, the program attempts to store the null-terminated string `"excessive"` with ASCII encoding in the A buffer.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] `"excessive"` is 9 characters long and encodes to 10 bytes including the null terminator, but `a` can take only 8 bytes.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] `b`'s value has now been inadvertently replaced by a number formed from part of the character string.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] In this example "e" followed by a zero byte would become 25856.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Writing data past the end of allocated memory can sometimes be detected by the operating system to generate a segmentation fault error that terminates the process.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] When available, the strlcpy library function is preferred over strncpy which does not null-terminate the destination buffer if the source string's length is greater than or equal to the size of the buffer (the third argument passed to the function).
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Therefore a may not be null-terminated and cannot be treated as a valid C-style string.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The techniques to exploit a buffer overflow vulnerability vary by architecture, operating system, and memory region.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] For example, exploitation on the heap (used for dynamically allocated memory), differs markedly from exploitation on the call stack.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] In general, heap exploitation depends on the heap manager used on the target system, while stack exploitation depends on the calling convention used by the architecture and compiler.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The attacker designs data to cause one of these exploits, then places this data in a buffer supplied to users by the vulnerable code.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] If the address of the user-supplied data used to affect the stack buffer overflow is unpredictable, exploiting a stack buffer overflow to cause remote code execution becomes much more difficult.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] One technique that can be used to exploit such a buffer overflow is called "trampolining".
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Here, an attacker will find a pointer to the vulnerable stack buffer and compute the location of their shellcode relative to that pointer.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The attacker will then use the overwrite to jump to an instruction already in memory which will make a second jump, this time relative to the pointer.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] That second jump will branch execution into the shellcode.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Suitable instructions are often present in large code.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The Metasploit Project, for example, maintains a database of suitable opcodes, though it lists only those found in the Windows operating system.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] A buffer overflow occurring in the heap data area is referred to as a heap overflow and is exploitable in a manner different from that of stack-based overflows.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Memory on the heap is dynamically allocated by the application at run-time and typically contains program data.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Exploitation is performed by corrupting this data in specific ways to cause the application to overwrite internal structures such as linked list pointers.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The canonical heap overflow technique overwrites dynamic memory allocation linkage (such as malloc meta data) and uses the resulting pointer exchange to overwrite a program function pointer.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Microsoft's GDI+ vulnerability in handling JPEGs is an example of the danger a heap overflow can present.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Manipulation of the buffer, which occurs before it is read or executed, may lead to the failure of an exploitation attempt.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] These manipulations can mitigate the threat of exploitation, but may not make it impossible.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Manipulations could include conversion to upper or lower case, removal of metacharacters and filtering out of non-alphanumeric strings.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] However, techniques exist to bypass these filters and manipulations, such as alphanumeric shellcode, polymorphic code, self-modifying code, and return-to-libc attacks.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The same methods can be used to avoid detection by intrusion detection systems.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] In some cases, including where code is converted into Unicode, the threat of the vulnerability has been misrepresented by the disclosers as only Denial of Service when in fact the remote execution of arbitrary code is possible.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] In real-world exploits there are a variety of challenges which need to be overcome for exploits to operate reliably.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] These factors include null bytes in addresses, variability in the location of shellcode, differences between environments, and various counter-measures in operation.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] A NOP-sled is the oldest and most widely known technique for exploiting stack buffer overflows.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] It solves the problem of finding the exact address of the buffer by effectively increasing the size of the target area.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] To do this, much larger sections of the stack are corrupted with the no-op machine instruction.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] At the end of the attacker-supplied data, after the no-op instructions, the attacker places an instruction to perform a relative jump to the top of the buffer where the shellcode is located.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This collection of no-ops is referred to as the "NOP-sled" because if the return address is overwritten with any address within the no-op region of the buffer, the execution will "slide" down the no-ops until it is redirected to the actual malicious code by the jump at the end.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This technique requires the attacker to guess where on the stack the NOP-sled is instead of the comparatively small shellcode.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Because of the popularity of this technique, many vendors of intrusion prevention systems will search for this pattern of no-op machine instructions in an attempt to detect shellcode in use.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] A NOP-sled does not necessarily contain only traditional no-op machine instructions.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Any instruction that does not corrupt the machine state to a point where the shellcode will not run can be used in place of the hardware assisted no-op.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] As a result, it has become common practice for exploit writers to compose the no-op sled with randomly chosen instructions which will have no real effect on the shellcode execution.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] While this method greatly improves the chances that an attack will be successful, it is not without problems.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Exploits using this technique still must rely on some amount of luck that they will guess offsets on the stack that are within the NOP-sled region.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] An incorrect guess will usually result in the target program crashing and could alert the system administrator to the attacker's activities.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Another problem is that the NOP-sled requires a much larger amount of memory in which to hold a NOP-sled large enough to be of any use.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This can be a problem when the allocated size of the affected buffer is too small and the current depth of the stack is shallow (i.e., there is not much space from the end of the current stack frame to the start of the stack).
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Despite its problems, the NOP-sled is often the only method that will work for a given platform, environment, or situation, and as such it is still an important technique.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The "jump to register" technique allows for reliable exploitation of stack buffer overflows without the need for extra room for a NOP-sled and without having to guess stack offsets.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The strategy is to overwrite the return pointer with something that will cause the program to jump to a known pointer stored within a register which points to the controlled buffer and thus the shellcode.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] For example, if register A contains a pointer to the start of a buffer then any jump or call taking that register as an operand can be used to gain control of the flow of execution.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] In practice a program may not intentionally contain instructions to jump to a particular register.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The traditional solution is to find an unintentional instance of a suitable opcode at a fixed location somewhere within the program memory.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Figure E on the left contains an example of such an unintentional instance of the i386 `jmp esp` instruction.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The opcode for this instruction is `FF E4`.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This two-byte sequence can be found at a one-byte offset from the start of the instruction `call DbgPrint` at address `0x7C941EED`.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] If an attacker overwrites the program return address with this address the program will first jump to `0x7C941EED`, interpret the opcode `FF E4` as the `jmp esp` instruction, and will then jump to the top of the stack and execute the attacker's code.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] When this technique is possible the severity of the vulnerability increases considerably.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This is because exploitation will work reliably enough to automate an attack with a virtual guarantee of success when it is run.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] For this reason, this is the technique most commonly used in Internet worms that exploit stack buffer overflow vulnerabilities.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This method also allows shellcode to be placed after the overwritten return address on the Windows platform.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Since executables are mostly based at address `0x00400000` and x86 is a little endian architecture, the last byte of the return address must be a null, which terminates the buffer copy and nothing is written beyond that.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This limits the size of the shellcode to the size of the buffer, which may be overly restrictive.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] DLLs are located in high memory (above `0x01000000`) and so have addresses containing no null bytes, so this method can remove null bytes (or other disallowed characters) from the overwritten return address.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Used in this way, the method is often referred to as **DLL trampolining**.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Various techniques have been used to detect or prevent buffer overflows, with various tradeoffs.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The following sections describe the choices and implementations available.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Assembly, C, and C++ are popular programming languages that are vulnerable to buffer overflow in part because they allow direct access to memory and are not strongly typed.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] C provides no built-in protection against accessing or overwriting data in any part of memory.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] More specifically, it does not check that data written to a buffer is within the boundaries of that buffer.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The standard C++ libraries provide many ways of safely buffering data, and C++'s Standard Template Library (STL) provides containers that can optionally perform bounds checking if the programmer explicitly calls for checks while accessing data.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] For example, a `vector`'s member function `at()` performs a bounds check and throws an `out_of_range` exception if the bounds check fails.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] However, C++ behaves just like C if the bounds check is not explicitly called.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Techniques to avoid buffer overflows also exist for C.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Languages that are strongly typed and do not allow direct memory access, such as COBOL, Java, Eiffel, Python, and others, prevent buffer overflow in most cases.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Examples of such languages include Ada, Eiffel, Lisp, Modula-2, Smalltalk, OCaml and some systems programming languages such as Cyclone, Rust and D.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The Java and .NET Framework bytecode environments also require bounds checking on all arrays.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Nearly every interpreted language will protect against buffer overflow, signaling a well-defined error condition.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Languages that provide enough type information to do bounds checking often provide an option to enable or disable it.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Static code analysis can remove many dynamic bound and type checks, but poor implementations and awkward cases can significantly decrease performance.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Software engineers should carefully consider the tradeoffs of safety versus performance costs when deciding which language and compiler setting to use.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The problem of buffer overflows is common in the C and C++ languages because they expose low level representational details of buffers as containers for data types.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Buffer overflows can be avoided by maintaining a high degree of correctness in code that performs buffer management.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] It has also long been recommended to avoid standard library functions that are not bounds checked, such as `gets`, `scanf` and `strcpy`.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The Morris worm exploited a `gets` call in fingerd.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Well-written and tested abstract data type libraries that centralize and automatically perform buffer management, including bounds checking, can reduce the occurrence and impact of buffer overflows.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The primary data types in languages in which buffer overflows are common are strings and arrays.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Thus, libraries preventing buffer overflows in these data types can provide the vast majority of the necessary coverage.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] However, failure to use these safe libraries correctly can result in buffer overflows and other vulnerabilities, and naturally any bug in the library is also a potential vulnerability.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] "Safe" library implementations include "The Better String Library", Vstr and Erwin.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The OpenBSD operating system's C library provides the strlcpy and strlcat functions, but these are more limited than full safe library implementations.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] In September 2007, Technical Report 24731, prepared by the C standards committee, was published.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] It specifies a set of functions that are based on the standard C library's string and IO functions, with additional buffer-size parameters.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] However, the efficacy of these functions for reducing buffer overflows is disputable.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] They require programmer intervention on a per function call basis that is equivalent to intervention that could make the analogous older standard library functions buffer overflow safe.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Buffer overflow protection is used to detect the most common buffer overflows by checking that the stack has not been altered when a function returns.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] If it has been altered, the program exits with a segmentation fault.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Three such systems are Libsafe, and the *StackGuard* and *ProPolice* gcc patches.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Microsoft's implementation of Data Execution Prevention (DEP) mode explicitly protects the pointer to the Structured Exception Handler (SEH) from being overwritten.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Stronger stack protection is possible by splitting the stack in two: one for data and one for function returns.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This split is present in the Forth language, though it was not a security-based design decision.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Regardless, this is not a complete solution to buffer overflows, as sensitive data other than the return address may still be overwritten.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This type of protection is also not entirely accurate because it does not detect all attacks.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Systems like StackGuard are more centered around the behavior of the attacks, which makes them efficient and faster in comparison to range-check systems.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Buffer overflows work by manipulating pointers, including stored addresses.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] PointGuard was proposed as a compiler-extension to prevent attackers from reliably manipulating pointers and addresses.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The approach works by having the compiler add code to automatically XOR-encode pointers before and after they are used.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Theoretically, because the attacker does not know what value will be used to encode and decode the pointer, one cannot predict what the pointer will point to if it is overwritten with a new value.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] PointGuard was never released, but Microsoft implemented a similar approach beginning in Windows XP SP2 and Windows Server 2003 SP1.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Rather than implement pointer protection as an automatic feature, Microsoft added an API routine that can be called.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This allows for better performance (because it is not used all of the time), but places the burden on the programmer to know when its use is necessary.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Because XOR is linear, an attacker may be able to manipulate an encoded pointer by overwriting only the lower bytes of an address.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This can allow an attack to succeed if the attacker can attempt the exploit multiple times or complete an attack by causing a pointer to point to one of several locations (such as any location within a NOP sled).
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Microsoft added a random rotation to their encoding scheme to address this weakness to partial overwrites.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Executable-space protection is an approach to buffer overflow protection that prevents execution of code on the stack or the heap.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] An attacker may use buffer overflows to insert arbitrary code into the memory of a program, but with executable-space protection, any attempt to execute that code will cause an exception.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Some CPUs support a feature called NX ("No eXecute") or XD ("eXecute Disabled") bit, which in conjunction with software, can be used to mark pages of data (such as those containing the stack and the heap) as readable and writable but not executable.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] OpenBSD, macOS) ship with executable-space protection (e.g.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Newer variants of Microsoft Windows also support executable-space protection, called Data Execution Prevention.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Executable-space protection does not generally protect against return-to-libc attacks, or any other attack that does not rely on the execution of the attackers code.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] However, on 64-bit systems using ASLR, as described below, executable-space protection makes it far more difficult to execute such attacks.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] CHERI (Capability Hardware Enhanced RISC Instructions) is a computer processor technology designed to improve security.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] It operates at a hardware level by providing a hardware-enforced type (a CHERI capability) that authorises access to memory.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Traditional pointers are replaced by addresses accompanied by metadata that limit what can be accessed through any given pointer.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Address space layout randomization (ASLR) is a computer security feature that involves arranging the positions of key data areas, usually including the base of the executable and position of libraries, heap, and stack, randomly in a process' address space.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Randomization of the virtual memory addresses at which functions and variables can be found can make exploitation of a buffer overflow more difficult, but not impossible.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] It also forces the attacker to tailor the exploitation attempt to the individual system, which foils the attempts of internet worms.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] A similar but less effective method is to rebase processes and libraries in the virtual address space.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The use of deep packet inspection (DPI) can detect, at the network perimeter, very basic remote attempts to exploit buffer overflows by use of attack signatures and heuristics.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This technique can block packets that have the signature of a known attack.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] It was formerly used in situations in which a long series of No-Operation instructions (known as a NOP-sled) was detected and the location of the exploit's payload was slightly variable.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Packet scanning is not an effective method since it can only prevent known attacks and there are many ways that a NOP-sled can be encoded.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Shellcode used by attackers can be made alphanumeric, metamorphic, or self-modifying to evade detection by heuristic packet scanners and intrusion detection systems.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Checking for buffer overflows and patching the bugs that cause them helps prevent buffer overflows.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] One common automated technique for discovering them is fuzzing.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Edge case testing can also uncover buffer overflows, as can static analysis.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Once a potential buffer overflow is detected it should be patched.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This makes the testing approach useful for software that is in development, but less useful for legacy software that is no longer maintained or supported.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] This can be used to inject code into the monitor that will permit the user to seize control of the machine." Today, the monitor would be referred to as the kernel.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The earliest documented hostile exploitation of a buffer overflow was in 1988.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] It was one of several exploits used by the Morris worm to propagate itself over the Internet.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The program exploited was a service on Unix called finger.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Later, in 1995, Thomas Lopatic independently rediscovered the buffer overflow and published his findings on the Bugtraq security mailing list.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] A year later, in 1996, Elias Levy (also known as Aleph One) published in *Phrack* magazine the paper "Smashing the Stack for Fun and Profit", a step-by-step introduction to exploiting stack-based buffer overflow vulnerabilities.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] Since then, at least two major internet worms have exploited buffer overflows to compromise a large number of systems.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] In 2001, the Code Red worm exploited a buffer overflow in Microsoft's Internet Information Services (IIS) 5.0 and in 2003 the SQL Slammer worm compromised machines running Microsoft SQL Server 2000.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] In 2003, buffer overflows present in licensed Xbox games have been exploited to allow unlicensed software, including homebrew games, to run on the console without the need for hardware modifications, known as modchips.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The PS2 Independence Exploit also used a buffer overflow to achieve the same for the PlayStation 2.
[src:data-execution-prevention/buffer-overflow] The Twilight hack accomplished the same with the Wii, using a buffer overflow in *The Legend of Zelda: Twilight Princess*.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] In computer security, **executable-space protection** marks memory regions as non-executable, such that an attempt to execute machine code in these regions will cause an exception.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] It relies on hardware features such as the NX bit (no-execute bit), or on software emulation when hardware support is unavailable.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Software emulation often introduces a performance cost, or overhead (extra processing time or resources), while hardware-based NX bit implementations have no measurable performance impact.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] The Burroughs large systems, starting with the Burroughs 5000 introduced in 1961, implemented executable-space protection using a tagged architecture.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] All accesses to code and data took place through descriptors, which had memory tags preventing them from being modified; descriptors for code did not allow the code to be modified, and descriptors for data did not allow the data to be executed as code.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Today, operating systems use executable-space protection to mark writable memory areas, such as the stack and heap, as non-executable, helping to prevent buffer overflow exploits.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] These attacks rely on some part of memory, usually the stack, being both writable and executable; if it is not, the attack fails.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Many operating systems implement or have an available executable space protection policy.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Here is a list of such systems in alphabetical order, each with technologies ordered from newest to oldest.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] A technology supplying Architecture Independent emulation will be functional on all processors which aren't hardware supported.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] The "Other Supported" line is for processors which allow some grey-area method, where an explicit NX bit doesn't exist yet hardware allows one to be emulated in some way.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] As of Android 2.3 and later, architectures which support it have non-executable pages by default, including non-executable stack and heap.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Initial support for the NX bit, on x86-64 and IA-32 processors that support it, first appeared in FreeBSD -CURRENT on June 8, 2004.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] It has been in FreeBSD releases since the 5.3 release.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] The Linux kernel supports the NX bit on x86-64 and IA-32 processors that support it, such as modern 64-bit processors made by AMD, Intel, Transmeta and VIA.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] The support for this feature in the 64-bit mode on x86-64 CPUs was added in 2004 by Andi Kleen, and later the same year, Ingo Molnár added support for it in 32-bit mode on 64-bit CPUs.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] These features have been part of the Linux kernel mainline since the release of kernel version 2.6.8 in August 2004.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Other processors that do not support PAE are AMD K6 and earlier, Transmeta Crusoe, VIA C3 and earlier, and Geode GX and LX.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] VMware Workstation versions older than 4.0, Parallels Workstation versions older than 4.0, and Microsoft Virtual PC and Virtual Server do not support PAE on the guest.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Fedora Core 6 and Ubuntu 9.10 and later provide a kernel-PAE package which supports PAE and NX.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] NX memory protection has always been available in Ubuntu for any systems that had the hardware to support it and ran the 64-bit kernel or the 32-bit server kernel.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] The 32-bit PAE desktop kernel (linux-image-generic-pae) in Ubuntu 9.10 and later, also provides the PAE mode needed for hardware with the NX CPU feature.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] For systems that lack NX hardware, the 32-bit kernels now provide an approximation of the NX CPU feature via software emulation that can help block many exploits an attacker might run from stack or heap memory.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Non-execute functionality has also been present for other non-x86 processors supporting this functionality for many releases.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Red Hat kernel developer Ingo Molnár released a Linux kernel patch named Exec Shield to approximate and utilize NX functionality on 32-bit x86 CPUs.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] The Exec Shield patch was released to the Linux kernel mailing list on May 2, 2003, but was rejected for merging with the base kernel because it involved some intrusive changes to core code in order to handle the complex parts of the emulation.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Exec Shield's legacy CPU support approximates NX emulation by tracking the upper code segment limit.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] This imposes only a few cycles of overhead during context switches, which is for all intents and purposes immeasurable.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] For legacy CPUs without an NX bit, Exec Shield fails to protect pages below the code segment limit; an mprotect() call to mark higher memory, such as the stack, executable will mark all memory below that limit executable as well.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Thus, in these situations, Exec Shield's schemes fails.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] This is the cost of Exec Shield's low overhead.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Exec Shield checks for two ELF header markings, which dictate whether the stack or heap needs to be executable.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] These are called PT_GNU_STACK and PT_GNU_HEAP respectively.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Exec Shield allows these controls to be set for both binary executables and for libraries; if an executable loads a library requiring a given restriction relaxed, the executable will inherit that marking and have that restriction relaxed.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] The PaX NX technology can emulate NX functionality, or use a hardware NX bit.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] PaX works on x86 CPUs that do not have the NX bit, such as 32-bit x86.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] The Linux kernel still does not ship with PaX (as of May, 2007); the patch must be merged manually.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] PaX provides two methods of NX bit emulation, called SEGMEXEC and PAGEEXEC.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] The SEGMEXEC method imposes a measurable but low overhead, typically less than 1%, which is a constant scalar incurred due to the virtual memory mirroring used for the separation between execution and data accesses.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] SEGMEXEC also has the effect of halving the task's virtual address space, allowing the task to access less memory than it normally could.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] This is not a problem until the task requires access to more than half the normal address space, which is rare.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] SEGMEXEC does not cause programs to use more system memory (i.e.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] RAM), it only restricts how much they can access.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] On 32-bit CPUs, this becomes 1.5 GB rather than 3 GB.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] PaX supplies a method similar to Exec Shield's approximation in the PAGEEXEC as a speedup; however, when higher memory is marked executable, this method loses its protections.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] In these cases, PaX falls back to the older, variable-overhead method used by PAGEEXEC to protect pages below the CS limit, which may become quite a high-overhead operation in certain memory access patterns.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] When the PAGEEXEC method is used on a CPU supplying a hardware NX bit, the hardware NX bit is used, thus no significant overhead is incurred.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] PaX supplies mprotect() restrictions to prevent programs from marking memory in ways that produce memory useful for a potential exploit.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] This policy causes certain applications to cease to function, but it can be disabled for affected programs.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] PaX ignores both PT_GNU_STACK and PT_GNU_HEAP.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] In the past, PaX had a configuration option to honor these settings but that option has been removed for security reasons, as it was deemed not useful.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] The same results of PT_GNU_STACK can normally be attained by disabling mprotect() restrictions, as the program will normally mprotect() the stack on load.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] This may not always be true; for situations where this fails, simply disabling both PAGEEXEC and SEGMEXEC will effectively remove all executable space restrictions, giving the task the same protections on its executable space as a non-PaX system.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] macOS for Intel supports the NX bit on all CPUs supported by Apple (from Mac OS X 10.4.4 – the first Intel release – onwards).
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Mac OS X 10.4 only supported NX stack protection.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] In Mac OS X 10.5, all 64-bit executables have NX stack and heap; W^X protection.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] This includes x86-64 (Core 2 or later) and 64-bit PowerPC on the G5 Macs.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] As of NetBSD 2.0 and later (December 9, 2004), architectures which support it have non-executable stack and heap.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Architectures that have per-page granularity consist of: alpha, amd64, hppa, i386 (with PAE), powerpc (ibm4xx), sh5, sparc (sun4m, sun4d), sparc64.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Architectures that can only support these with region granularity are: i386 (without PAE), other powerpc (such as macppc).
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Other architectures do not benefit from non-executable stack or heap; NetBSD does not by default use any software emulation to offer these features on those architectures.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] A technology in the OpenBSD operating system, known as W^X, marks writable pages by default as non-executable on processors that support that.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] On 32-bit x86 processors, the code segment is set to include only part of the address space, to provide some level of executable space protection.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] OpenBSD 3.3 shipped May 1, 2003, and was the first to include W^X.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Solaris has supported globally disabling stack execution on SPARC processors since Solaris 2.6 (1997); in Solaris 9 (2002), support for disabling stack execution on a per-executable basis was added.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] The first implementation of a non-executable stack for Windows (NT 4.0, 2000 and XP) was published by SecureWave via their SecureStack product in 2001, based on the work of PaX.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Starting with Windows XP Service Pack 2 (2004) and Windows Server 2003 Service Pack 1 (2005), the NX features were implemented for the first time on the x86 architecture.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Executable space protection on Windows is called "Data Execution Prevention" (DEP).
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Under Windows XP or Server 2003 NX protection was used on critical Windows services exclusively by default.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] If the x86 processor supported this feature in hardware, then the NX features were turned on automatically in Windows XP/Server 2003 by default.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] If the feature was not supported by the x86 processor, then no protection was given.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Early implementations of DEP provided no address space layout randomization (ASLR), which allowed potential return-to-libc attacks that could have been feasibly used to disable DEP during an attack.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] The PaX documentation elaborates on why ASLR is necessary; a proof-of-concept was produced detailing a method by which DEP could be circumvented in the absence of ASLR.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] It may be possible to develop a successful attack if the address of prepared data such as corrupted images or MP3s can be known by the attacker.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Microsoft added ASLR functionality in Windows Vista and Windows Server 2008.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] On this platform, DEP is implemented through the automatic use of PAE kernel in 32-bit Windows and the native support on 64-bit kernels.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Windows Vista DEP works by marking certain parts of memory as being intended to hold only data, which the NX or XD bit enabled processor then understands as non-executable.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] In Windows, from version Vista, whether DEP is enabled or disabled for a particular process can be viewed on the *Processes/Details* tab in the Windows Task Manager.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Windows implements software DEP (without the use of the NX bit) through Microsoft's "Safe Structured Exception Handling" (SafeSEH).
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] For properly compiled applications, SafeSEH checks that, when an exception is raised during program execution, the exception's handler is one defined by the application as it was originally compiled.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] The effect of this protection is that an attacker is not able to add his own exception handler which he has stored in a data page through unchecked program input.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] When NX is supported, it is enabled by default.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Windows allows programs to control which pages disallow execution through its API as well as through the section headers in a PE file.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] In the API, runtime access to the NX bit is exposed through the Win32 API calls VirtualAlloc[Ex] and VirtualProtect[Ex].
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Each page may be individually flagged as executable or non-executable.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Despite the lack of previous x86 hardware support, both executable and non-executable page settings have been provided since the beginning.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] On pre-NX CPUs, the presence of the 'executable' attribute has no effect.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] It was documented as if it did function, and, as a result, most programmers used it properly.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] In the PE file format, each section can specify its executability.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] The execution flag has existed since the beginning of the format and standard linkers have always used this flag correctly, even long before the NX bit.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Because of this, Windows is able to enforce the NX bit on old programs.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Assuming the programmer complied with "best practices", applications should work correctly now that NX is actually enforced.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Only in a few cases have there been problems; Microsoft's own .NET Runtime had problems with the NX bit and was updated.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] In Microsoft's Xbox, although the CPU does not have the NX bit, newer versions of the XDK set the code segment limit to the beginning of the kernel's **.data** section (no code should be after this point in normal circumstances).
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Starting with version 51xx, this change was also implemented into the kernel of new Xboxes.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] This broke the techniques old exploits used to become a terminate-and-stay-resident program.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] However, new exploits were quickly released supporting this new kernel version because the fundamental vulnerability in the Xbox kernel was unaffected.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Where code is written and executed at runtime—a JIT compiler is a prominent example—the compiler can potentially be used to produce exploit code (e.g. using JIT Spray) that has been flagged for execution and therefore would not be trapped.
[src:data-execution-prevention/data-execution-prevention] Return-oriented programming can allow an attacker to execute arbitrary code even when executable space protection is enforced.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] The **NX bit** (**no-execute bit**) is a processor feature that separates areas of a virtual address space (the memory layout a program uses) into sections for storing data or program instructions.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] An operating system supporting the NX bit can mark certain areas of the virtual address space as non-executable, preventing the processor from running any code stored there.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] This technique, known as executable-space protection or Write XOR Execute, protects computers from malicious software that attempts to insert harmful code into another program’s data storage area and execute it, such as in a buffer overflow attack.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] The term "NX bit" was introduced by Advanced Micro Devices (AMD) as a marketing term.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] Intel markets this feature as the **XD bit** (**execute disable**), while the MIPS architecture refers to it as the **XI bit** (**execute inhibit**).
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] In the ARM architecture, introduced in ARMv6, it is known as **XN** (**execute never**).
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] The term NX bit is often used broadly to describe similar executable-space protection technologies in other processors.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] x86 processors, since the 80286, included a similar capability implemented at the segment level.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] However, almost all operating systems for the 80386 and later x86 processors implement the flat memory model, so they cannot use this capability.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] Intel implemented a similar feature in its Itanium (*Merced*) processor—having IA-64 architecture—in 2001, but did not bring it to the more popular x86 processor families (Pentium, Celeron, Xeon, etc.).
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] In the x86 architecture it was first implemented by AMD, as the *NX bit*, for use by its AMD64 line of processors, such as the Athlon 64 and Opteron.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] After AMD's decision to include this functionality in its AMD64 instruction set, Intel implemented the similar XD bit feature in x86 processors beginning with the Pentium 4 processors based on later iterations of the Prescott core.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] The NX bit specifically refers to bit number 63 (i.e. the most significant bit) of a 64-bit entry in the page table.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] If this bit is set to 0, then code can be executed from that page; if set to 1, code cannot be executed from that page, and anything residing there is assumed to be data.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] It is only available with the long mode (64-bit mode) or legacy Physical Address Extension (PAE) page-table formats, but not x86's original 32-bit page table format because page table entries in that format lack the 64th bit used to disable and enable execution.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] Windows XP SP2 and later support Data Execution Prevention (DEP).
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] In ARMv6, a new page table entry format was introduced; it includes an "execute never" bit.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] As of the Fourth Edition of the Alpha Architecture manual, DEC (now HP) Alpha has a Fault on Execute bit in page table entries with the OpenVMS, Tru64 UNIX, and Alpha Linux PALcode.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] The SPARC Reference MMU for Sun SPARC version 8 has permission values of Read Only, Read/Write, Read/Execute, and Read/Write/Execute in page table entries, although not all SPARC processors have a SPARC Reference MMU.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] A SPARC version 9 MMU may provide, but is not required to provide, any combination of read/write/execute permissions.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] A Translation Table Entry in a Translation Storage Buffer in Oracle SPARC Architecture 2011, Draft D1.0.0 has separate Executable and Writable bits.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] Page table entries for IBM PowerPC's hashed page tables have a no-execute page bit.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] Page table entries for radix-tree page tables in the Power ISA have separate permission bits granting read/write and execute access.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] Translation lookaside buffer (TLB) entries and page table entries in PA-RISC 1.1 and PA-RISC 2.0 support read-only, read/write, read/execute, and read/write/execute pages.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] TLB entries in Itanium support read-only, read/write, read/execute, and read/write/execute pages.
[src:data-execution-prevention/nx-bit] As of the twelfth edition of the z/Architecture Principles of Operation, z/Architecture processors may support the Instruction-Execution Protection facility, which adds a bit in page table entries that controls whether instructions from a given region, segment, or page can be executed.
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] The first example of this attack in the wild was contributed by Alexander Peslyak on the Bugtraq mailing list in 1997.
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] On POSIX-compliant operating systems the C standard library ("`libc`") is commonly used to provide a standard runtime environment for programs written in the C programming language.
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] Although the attacker could make the code return anywhere, `libc` is the most likely target, as it is almost always linked to the program, and it provides useful calls for an attacker (such as the `system` function used to execute shell commands).
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] A non-executable stack can prevent some buffer overflow exploitation, however it cannot prevent a return-to-libc attack because in the return-to-libc attack only existing executable code is used.
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] On the other hand, these attacks can only call preexisting functions.
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] Stack-smashing protection can prevent or obstruct exploitation as it may detect the corruption of the stack and possibly flush out the compromised segment.
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] "ASCII armoring" is a technique that can be used to obstruct this kind of attack.
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] With ASCII armoring, all the system libraries (e.g., libc) addresses contain a NULL byte (`0x00`).
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] This is commonly done by placing them in the first `0x01010101` bytes of memory (a few pages more than 16 MB, dubbed the "ASCII armor region"), as every address up to (but not including) this value contains at least one NULL byte.
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] This makes it impossible to emplace code containing those addresses using string manipulation functions such as `strcpy()`.
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] However, this technique does not work if the attacker has a way to overflow NULL bytes into the stack.
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] If the program is too large to fit in the first 16 MB, protection may be incomplete.
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] This technique can be overcome by another attack known as **return-to-plt** where, instead of returning to libc, the attacker uses the Procedure Linkage Table (PLT) functions loaded in the position-independent code (e.g., `system@plt, execve@plt, sprintf@plt, strcpy@plt`).
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] Address space layout randomization (ASLR) makes this type of attack extremely unlikely to succeed on 64-bit machines as the memory locations of functions are random.
[src:data-execution-prevention/return-to-libc-attack] For 32-bit systems, however, ASLR provides little benefit since there are only 16 bits available for randomization, and they can be defeated by brute force in a matter of minutes.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] The terminology was first introduced in 2003 for Unix-like systems, but is today also used by some multi-platform systems (such as .NET).
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] Other operating systems have adopted similar policies under different names (e.g., DEP in Windows).
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] On Unix-like operating system kernels, like the Linux kernel or XNU, or those used in as components in larger operating systems like FreeBSD, OpenBSD, Solaris, and the UNIX System Services of Z/OS, W^X is controlled via the mprotect system call.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] It is relatively simple on processor architectures supporting fine-grained page permissions, such as SPARC, x86-64, PA-RISC, Alpha, and ARM.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] The term W^X has also been applied to file system write/execute permissions to mitigate file write vulnerabilities (as with in memory) and attacker persistence.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] Enforcing restrictions on file permissions can also close gaps in W^X enforcement caused by memory mapped files.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] Outright forbidding the usage of arbitrary native code can also mitigate kernel and CPU vulnerabilities not exposed via the existing code on the computer.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] A less intrusive approach is to lock a file for the duration of any mapping into executable memory, which suffices to prevent post-inspection bypasses.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] Some early Intel 64 processors lacked the NX bit required for W^X, but this appeared in later chips.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] On more limited processors such as the Intel i386, W^X requires using the CS code segment limit as a "line in the sand", a point in the address space above which execution is not permitted and data is located, and below which it is allowed and executable pages are placed.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] Linker changes are generally required to separate data from code (such as trampolines that are needed for linker and library runtime functions).
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] W^X can also pose a minor problem for just-in-time compilation, which involves an interpreter generating machine code on the fly and then running it.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] The simple solution used by most, historically including Firefox, involves just making the page executable after the interpreter is done writing machine code, using `VirtualProtect` on Windows or `mprotect` on Unix-like operating systems.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] The other solution involves mapping the same region of memory to two pages, one with RW and the other with RX.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] Supporters of the former approach believe that the latter approach is only safe when the two pages are given to two separate processes, and inter-process communication would be costlier than calling `mprotect`.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] W^X was first implemented in OpenBSD 3.3, released May 2003.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] In 2004, Microsoft introduced a similar feature called DEP (Data Execution Prevention) in Windows XP.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] Similar features are available for other operating systems, including the PaX and Exec Shield patches for Linux, and NetBSD's implementation of PaX.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] In Red Hat Enterprise Linux (and automatically CentOS) version 5, or by Linux Kernel 2.6.18-8, SELinux received the `allow_execmem`, `allow_execheap`, and `allow_execmod` policies that provide W^X when disabled.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] Although W^X (or DEP) has only protected userland programs for most of its existence, in 2012 Microsoft extended it to the Windows kernel on the x86 and ARM architectures.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] In late 2014 and early 2015, W^X was added in the OpenBSD kernel on the AMD64 architecture.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] In early 2016, W^X was fully implemented on NetBSD's AMD64 kernel and partially on the i386 kernel.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] macOS computers running on Apple silicon processors enforce W^X for all programs.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] Intel-based Macs enforce the policy only for programs that use the OS's Hardened Runtime mode.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] Starting with Firefox 46 in 2016 and ending with Firefox 116 in 2023, Firefox's virtual machine for JavaScript implemented the W^X policy.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] This was later rolled back on some platforms for performance reasons, though remained in others which enforce W^X for all programs.
[src:data-execution-prevention/w-x] .NET uses W^X starting with .NET 6.0 in 2021.
